column1: What will be the outcome of Hungary's referendum on the European Union's right to set quotas for migrant relocation?
column5: ['Turnout will reach or exceed 50% and a majority will vote "Yes"', 'Turnout will reach or exceed 50% and a majority will vote "No"', 'Turnout will not reach 50%']
column6: ['Elections and Referenda']
column11: This question was closed on option C ('Turnout will not reach 50%') with a closing date of 1 October 2016. Although over 98% of voters approved the referendum, fewer than 50% of eligible voters participated (The Guardian, NPR, CNN). This is an updated version of previously voided question. For forecasts made on a the prior version see here. A referendum scheduled for 2 October 2016 asks Hungarian voters: "Do you want to allow the European Union to mandate the resettlement of non-Hungarian citizens to Hungary without the approval of the National Assembly?" According to Hungarian law, 50% of the population must participate in the referendum for it to be valid (See Article 8, Paragraph 4 of the Hungarian Constitution). For more information on the upcoming referendum see: BBC, Reuters, Bloomberg. Recommended Questions Will more than 1 million refugees and migrants arrive in Europe by sea in 2016? Before 2018, will it be officially announced that any state is withdrawing from the Schengen agreement? Will the EU lift visa requirements for Turkish citizens before the end of 2016?

New poll results are out today and it seems only 46% said they would definitely go.

The poll in the Hungarian Free Press (see Anneinak below) seems out of step with other polls. http://hungarianfreepress.com/2016/09/28/new-poll-spells-trouble-for-orban-ahead-of-hungarys-referendum/ https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hungarian_migrant_quota_referendum,_2016 but none of the polls forecast much over 50% of the electorate as intending to vote (and some give under 50%, as Anneiak says polls (probably) overstate the likelihood that voters will actually turn out. In previous referendums in Hungary the turnout has not been nearly as high as in elections and most have failed to achieve the 50%. There seems to be little motivation for voters to bother to go to the polling station. According to The Economist a NO vote that beats a YES vote by a significant percentage sends a clear message to the EU regardless of the turnout being a few percentage points above or below 50%. Getting 75% voting NO on a 40% turnout gets the message across as clearly as getting 60% NO on a 51% turnout. That message is that the EU telling Hungary to accept a fixed number of refugees is not popular in Hungary. It does not appear that getting over 50% would actually trigger anything. The EU plan to direct countries to take refugees is probably already dead.

Turnout in Hungarian referendums since 1997 have been 49.2%, 45.6%, 37.5%, and 50.5%. Weighted due to relevance and how recent the referendums took place, I developed a weighted average of c.42%. The average turnout intention in polling for the referendum has been 51%. With the absence of any empirical data, I take both these percentages to be of equal weight, giving me an estimated turnout percentage of 46.5%. This should be tempered by the fact that these referendums have been votes "for" something rather than "against" as is the case here. All this being said, the likelihood of turnout exceeding 50% is in my view, 35%.

EU-imposed quotas is a very unpopular issue and no one is spending political capital arguing in favour of them. Even the pro-EU forces are concentrating mainly on a boycott campaign. As such, while not impossible, a "Yes" victory is a very remote possibility.

From what we read in the papers and see on the world news shows, European countries are starting to shift away from open borders. This includes historically liberal counties like Denmark and Sweden. And with terrorism, crime and unemployment increasing I would expect this shift to continue.
The government is using the referendum to win support in favor of a "no" vote. The opposition to EU mandates will also play a part.

Having looked at https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hungarian_migrant_quota_referendum,_2016 poll data and https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Category:Referendums_in_Hungary data on turnout in previous referendums, and taking into account that several opposition parties want their supporters to boycott the vote, I have revised my forecast. Although the questions sounds as if it would prompt a high turnout the polls seem to suggest that only about half of voters are actually interested. Maybe they assume (probably correctly) that the result will not actually make any difference.

Increasing probability of <50% turnout. the questionseems dependent on how motivated the electorate will be. --Hungarians have turned out in >50% numbers to pass both NATO and EU membership referendums, and for the abolishment of certain fees. They have failed to turn out for dual citizenship and presidential election rules referendum. This referendum is likely not as motivational as the prior referendums that passed due to:

The polls seem to predict a clear "No". The questions has been framed to enourage a "No". If we assume that the governing party (Fidesz) and the far right (Jobbik) party's voters will vote "No" that would give about 65% of the electorate. In parliamentary elections there has been over 60% turnout. Right wing, populist and nativist rhetoric has been getting good results in polls in the last few years (Trump in primaries, Brexit, Le Pen etc.) The only likely way for "No" to "lose" would be if the third of voters who did not support Feidesz or Jobbik boycotted the referendum or spoiled their ballot papers. If they all did this "No" could overwhelmingly win the vote, but the total number of votes would be below the 50% threshold and nullify the result. It sets a risky precedent to tell your supports not to turn up to vote. So far some opposition parties are urging a boycot or to spoil the ballot but others are telling supporters to vote "yes".

The Fidesz party does not want to lose supporters to Jobbik so it takes their anti-immigrant policy from them, which is not unusual in Europe for leaders to talk not unlike the right wing parties to keep supporters. For Hungary, given their nation between the east and west, Christianity and Islam, Hungary and the Ottoman war, they generally have to balance their policy when they need to do so.
